    <h2>Electricity and Gas Requirements</h2>

    <p>Understanding utility requirements before purchase prevents costly surprises. Here is what you need:</p>

    <h3>Electrical Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Semi-auto machines:</strong> Single phase, 220V, 1–2 kW. A standard 15A socket is usually sufficient.</li>
      <li><strong>Fully automatic machines:</strong> Three-phase, 440V, 3–7 kW. You will need a 3-phase connection and a dedicated MCB/MCCB breaker.</li>
      <li><strong>Industrial lines:</strong> Three-phase, 440V, 7–15 kW. May require a dedicated transformer in some locations.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>If you do not already have a 3-phase connection, applying for one from your electricity board typically costs ₹5,000–₹25,000 and takes 1–4 weeks. Factor this into your setup timeline.</p>

    <h3>Gas Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>LPG consumption:</strong> A typical fully automatic chapati machine uses 1–3 kg of LPG per hour during operation. At current commercial LPG rates (~₹75/kg), that translates to ₹75–225/hour in gas costs.</li>
      <li><strong>PNG (piped natural gas):</strong> If available in your area, PNG is 30–40% cheaper than LPG. Conversion kits are available for most machines. Monthly PNG cost for a medium machine: ₹4,000–₹10,000.</li>
      <li><strong>Puri fryer gas usage:</strong> Continuous puri fryers are gas-hungry — expect 2–5 kg LPG per hour depending on fryer size and oil volume.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Always ensure adequate ventilation when using gas-fired equipment. A commercial <a href="/blog/commercial-exhaust-hood">exhaust hood</a> with proper ducting is mandatory for safety and is required under <a href="/blog/fssai-license-cost-registration-india">FSSAI regulations</a>.</p>

